                        <div id="content" class="hfeed">
                            <article class="post-157479 post type-post status-publish hentry category-private-lives tag-aneurysms tag-brain tag-surgery-and-surgeons des-aneurysms des-brain des-surgery-and-surgeons news_keywords-aneurysm news_keywords-brain news_keywords-surgery-2"
                                id="post-157479">
                                <header class="postHeader">
                                    <div class="postKicker">
                                        <span class="kicker"><a href="//opinionator.blogs.nytimes.com/category/private-lives/?module=BlogCategory&amp;version=Blog Post&amp;action=Click&amp;contentCollection=Opinion&amp;pgtype=Blogs&amp;region=Header">Private Lives</a></span>
                                    </div>
                                    <h1 itemprop="headline" class="entry-title">Bonding Over Brain Surgery</h1>
                                    <div class="story-meta-footer">
                                        <address class="byline author vcard" itemprop="author creator" itemtype="//schema.org/Person">
				By Jett Stone			</address>
                                        <!-- date published --><time class="dateline " datetime="2015-06-25T10:45:45+00:00" itemprop="datePublished">June 25, 2015 6:45 am</time>
                                        <!-- date updated --><span class="visually-hidden updated">June 25, 2015 6:45 am</span><button class="button comments-button  theme-kicker" data-skip-to-para-id="">
</button>
                                    </div>
                                </header>
                                <div class="entry-content">
                                    <div class="inlineModule">
                                        <div class="entry">
                                            <div class="thumb"><img alt="Private Lives" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/blogs_v3/firstperson/firstperson45.png" width="50" height="50"></div>
                                            <p class="summary"> <a href="//opinionator.blogs.nytimes.com/category/private-lives/">Private Lives:</a> Personal essays on the news of the world and the news of our lives.
                                            </p>
                                        </div>
                                    </div>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">My parents&#x2019; bedroom in my childhood home doubled as my dad&#x2019;s neurosurgical haven, and it offered a glimpse into his work as a brain surgeon in the 1980s and &#x2019;90s. Various-size real human and primate
                                        skulls (available to medical students in the early 1970s), brain models and endless books surrounded their bedroom furniture. My mother, an artist, fed his passion and likened the room to his studio space, understanding
                                        that her husband&#x2019;s true gallery was the operating room.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">As young kids my older sister and I would saunter into their room, and my dad would excitedly spin around in his wooden office chair to face us, pull out a medical book with colorfully drawn cross sections of the brain,
                                        and try to inspire our curiosity. What a thrill it was to capture this brilliant creature, peacefully perched in his nest of neuroanatomy.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">He had several white Styrofoam mannequin display heads that he used in demonstrations to medical students, and for head injury photographs in his academic papers. As we grew older, he repurposed these heads for our
                                        anatomy lessons. There was one mannequin that had a rod piercing up through its cheek, poking out through the top of the head. It was his talisman; he kept it close to a framed picture of my mom when she was young.
                                        More than once he used this mannequin to tell the story of Phineas Gage, a railroad laborer in the 1800s who survived a work accident in which an iron pole similarly struck and penetrated his head. My dad would
                                        go into the minutiae of how to operate on such a catastrophic injury, seemingly forgetting that&#xA0;we were not his eager medical students. I regret not being a more attentive pupil, but I realize now that there
                                        was much deeper meaning to his gestures than merely teaching us about his profession; he was conveying to us an important part of his otherwise inaccessible identity.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span id="more-157479"></span></p>
                                    <div class="w480">
                                        <figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/06/25/opinion/25PRIVATE/25PRIVATE-blog480.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span>
                                            <div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/06/25/opinion/25PRIVATE/25PRIVATE-blog480.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/06/25/opinion/25PRIVATE/25PRIVATE-blog480.jpg" id="100000003761804"
                                                    width="480" height="426" alt="">
                                                <meta itemprop="height" content="426">
                                                <meta itemprop="width" content="480">
                                            </div>
                                            <figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text"></span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Lando</span>
                                            </figcaption>
                                        </figure>
                                    </div>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Despite the unconventional d&#xE9;cor of their room, it carried an air of calmness and security, just like my dad, and that&#x2019;s what I gravitated toward. If I skinned my knee, I would be consoled just by the idea
                                        of running to their room to have him patch me up.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">But my sister and I also understood that his work could pull him away. As young kids, our bedtime stories would often be interrupted by phone calls conducted in secret jargon, and we would try to coax him back to finish
                                        the story, not fully comprehending why he had to leave so quickly to his secret world.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">As a teenager, I began noticing how my dad&#x2019;s composure stood in stark contrast to the intensity and traumas of his profession &#x2014; so much so that I found it puzzling. He always came home from work happy,
                                        eager to play catch, or show my sister and me what a cell looked like under a microscope; but there were times when I wished he would let loose a primal scream, just so I could bear witness to some elusive angst.
                                        He never did.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">When I was older, my dad would allow me to view more graphic images of brain surgery, and I would imagine his scalpel maneuvering amid the pulsating red-gray blob of dark purple highways and weaving side roads. Still,
                                        this work version of my dad seemed unreal, a simulation constructed of Styrofoam. Often I wondered if he was nervous about stepping into the operating arena and having to try to save other Phineas Gages in distress.
                                        I&#x2019;d hear his constant work calls about subdural hematomas, tumors&#xA0;and aneurysms interspersed with the words &#x201C;risk<em>&#x201D; </em>or &#x201C;emergency.&#x201D; I found it hard to envision this
                                        skinny man emerging from his phone booth like Superman to fight these faceless enemies.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Even though he was immersed in this opaque, complex world, he never stopped attempting to make it more transparent and accessible. Science was one of the conduits of our connection. And the content of what he said when
                                        we bonded over brain surgery may have been lost on me, but the implication was always clear:&#xA0;<em>I trust you, and grant you a window to my secret world.</em></p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Strangely, two years ago I shared another, more sobering, neurosurgical experience with my dad. But this time his dark, curly hair had transformed to white whiskers and the object of interest was no mannequin Styrofoam
                                        head. It was his wife.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">My parents were visiting New York from the Midwest because my sister was having her first baby. But a couple of days after my nephew&#x2019;s birth, my mom experienced a sudden severe head- and neck-ache. She said it
                                        was nothing a Tylenol could not fix. But my dad sensed something was awry and took her to the nearest emergency department. It was a lifesaving decision, as she soon learned that she had a ruptured brain aneurysm:
                                        a daunting diagnosis that my dad had uttered so often before in secret phone conversations before leaving hastily for the hospital.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">I recall sitting in the waiting room next to my dad, who was now stuck powerlessly outside the operating room as surgeons worked to save his wife. He was uncomfortably silent, and again I wondered if he was nervous.
                                        Then he pulled a pen from his shirt pocket and began drawing his wife&#x2019;s arteries and ballooning blood vessel, narrating the scene for me on his empty Starbucks cup. For a moment, he forgot that this was not
                                        his patient, but the girl he had boldly approached on a street 38 years earlier and eloped with two months afterward. Much like his detailed account of Phineas Gage&#x2019;s injuries, he spoke calmly, and I understood
                                        very little, mostly finding solace in the soothing tenor of the man who once read me bedtime stories.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">After my mom&#x2019;s operation, my dad lay alongside my mom on a cot for nearly two weeks, sleepless from the sounds of the 24-hour intensive care unit. As she began to recover, he blossomed. They were renewing their
                                        bond on the altar of brain science, and my dad seemed ever more in love. But as my mom returned to good health, he became eager to flip the script and return to being a surgeon. After a few days, he was finally
                                        able to retreat to the comforts of his secret life that was now less a secret to us all.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#xA0;</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em>Jett Stone is a writer who is studying for a Ph.D. in clinical psychology.</em></p>
                                </div>
                                <footer class="entry-footer">
